<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Corollary"
         id="Thm_BolzanoWeierstrass"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Bolzano-Weierstraß Theorem</caption>
   <associate type="Comment">
      <info>
         <info.caption>
            <caption>Comment</caption>
         </info.caption>
         <para>
            <para.body>The Bolzano-Weierstraß theorem was first proved by Bolzano in 1817 as a step toward a proof of the intermediate value theorem. About half a century later the theorem was rediscovered by Karl Weierstraß.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>Every bounded sequence <math>
               <latex>(x_n)</latex>
            </math> in <math>
               <latex>\RNr</latex>
            </math> has a convergent subsequence.
			</para.body>
         <index.author>
            <name>
               <name>
                  <first>Bernhard</first>
                  <middle>Placidus, Johann, Nepomuk</middle>
                  <last>Bolzano</last>
               </name>
            </name>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Appears here in connection with the Bolzano-Weierstraß theorem in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </info>
         </index.author>
         <index.author>
            <name>
               <name>
                  <first>Karl</first>
                  <last>Weierstraß</last>
               </name>
            </name>
            <info>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Appears here in connection with the Bolzano-Weierstraß theorem in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
            </info>
         </index.author>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>Bolzano-Weierstraß theorem</term>
            <info>
               <info.caption>
                  <caption>Bolzano-Weierstraß theorem</caption>
               </info.caption>
               <para>
                  <para.body>Every bounded sequence in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> has a convergent subsequence.</para.body>
               </para>
            </info>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof>
      <proof.block>
         <proof.block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>We show that <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> has a monotone subsequence. This implies the claim by the theorem on <subordinate>
                     <hot>monotone bounded convergence</hot>
                     <crossref>
                        <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_MonotoneBoundedSequenceConverges"/>
                     </crossref>
                  </subordinate>. Let us say that <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> takes a dip a <math>
                     <latex>n</latex>
                  </math> if all <math>
                     <latex> m&gt;n </latex>
                  </math> satisfy <math>
                     <latex>x_m\geq x_n</latex>
                  </math>. We know distinguish 3 cases:</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <emphasis>Case 1:</emphasis>
                  <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math>
                  <emphasis>takes no dip</emphasis>   Then <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> has a monotone decreasing subsequence for the following reason: Let <math>
                     <latex>n_0:=0</latex>
                  </math>. Then let <math>
                     <latex>n_1\geq 1</latex>
                  </math> be the least integer for which <math>
                     <latex>x_{n_1}\leq x_{n_0}</latex>
                  </math>. Then let <math>
                     <latex>n_2\geq n_1+1</latex>
                  </math> be the least integer for which <math>
                     <latex>x_{n_2}\leq x_{n_1}</latex>
                  </math>, etc. – These <math>
                     <latex>n_k</latex>
                  </math> exist because <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> takes no dip anywhere. By design <math>
                     <latex>(x_{n_i})</latex>
                  </math> is monotone decreasing. It is bounded below. So it converges.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <emphasis>Case 2</emphasis>
                  <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math>
                  <emphasis>takes only finitely many dips</emphasis>   Let <math>
                     <latex>K</latex>
                  </math> be the largest index at which <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math> takes a dip. Then the subsequence <math>
                     <latex>(x_n | n\geq K+1)</latex>
                  </math> takes no dip, hence has a monotone decreasing subsequence by Case 1.</para.body>
            </para>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <emphasis>Case 3</emphasis>
                  <math>
                     <latex>(x_n)</latex>
                  </math>
                  <emphasis>takes infinitely many dips</emphasis>   at numbers <math>
                     <latex> n_0 &lt; n_1 &lt; \dots &lt; n_k &lt; \dots </latex>
                  </math>. By definition, <math>
                     <latex>x_{n_0}\leq x_{n_1}\leq \dots \leq x_{n_k}\leq \dots </latex>
                  </math>. So <math>
                     <latex>(x_{n_k})</latex>
                  </math> is a monotone increasing subsequence. It is bounded above, hence converges.</para.body>
            </para>
         </proof.block.body>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
